
Q 11 Pull files from GitHub, make changes, and push back.

git config --global user.name "Your Name"            --- Set Git username
git config --global user.email "your_email@example.com" --- Set Git email
git clone <repository_url>      # Clone remote repo to local machine
cd <repo_name>                  # Go into project directory
nano file.txt                   # Edit file
git status                      # View changes
git add file.txt                # Stage specific file (optional)
git commit -m "Message"         # Commit staged changes
git pull origin main            # Sync with remote branch
git push origin main            # Push changes
git log                         # View commit history
git remote -v                   # Check remote repo URL

Q{14} Execute basic Git commands.

1. Create an AWS instance (T3a.small) and connect it using PuTTY  
2. Update and upgrade system packages  
3. Install Git and verify installation  
4. Perform basic Git operations to manage version control  

commands:-
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade -y      --- Update and upgrade system packages
sudo apt-get install git -y                          --- Install Git
git --version                                        --- Check installed Git version
git config --global user.name "Your Name"            --- Set your Git username
git config --global user.email "your_email@example.com" --- Set your Git email
git config --list                                   --- Verify Git configurations
mkdir myproject                                     --- Create a new project directory
cd myproject                                        --- Navigate into project folder
git init                                            --- Initialize a new Git repository
ls -a                                               --- View hidden .git folder
touch file.txt                                      --- Create a new file
git status                                          --- Check status of changes
git add .                                           --- Stage all changes
git commit -m "Initial commit"                      --- Commit staged files with a message
git log                                             --- View commit history
git remote add origin <repository_url>              --- Connect local repo to remote GitHub repo
git push -u origin main                             --- Push committed code to main branch
git pull origin main                                --- Pull latest changes from remote repository

Q{15} Create Git repository → add file → commit → push.

1. Create an AWS instance (T3a.small) and connect it using PuTTY  
2. Update and upgrade system packages  
3. Install Git and verify installation  
4. Create a new project directory and initialize a Git repository  
5. Add files, commit the changes, and push them to GitHub  

commands:-
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade -y      --- Update and upgrade system packages
sudo apt-get install git -y                          --- Install Git
git --version                                        --- Verify Git installation
git config --global user.name "Your Name"            --- Set Git username
git config --global user.email "your_email@example.com" --- Set Git email

mkdir myproject                                     --- Create new project directory
cd myproject                                        --- Navigate into project folder
git init                                            --- Initialize a new Git repository
ls -a                                        s       --- Verify .git folder created

touch index.html                                    --- Create a new file
nano index.html                                     --- Open file to edit (add sample content)
git status                                          --- Check status of repository
git add .                                           --- Stage all files for commit
git commit -m "Initial project setup"               --- Commit changes with message
git log                                             --- View commit history

git remote add origin <repository_url>              --- Connect local repo to remote GitHub repo
git branch -M main                                  --- Rename default branch to main
git push -u origin main                             --- Push committed code to GitHub repository






